problem: If $f(x)=\dfrac{x+1}{3x-4}$, what is the value of $f(5)$?
model_solution:
Step 1: Substitute $x = 5$ into the equation $f(x) = \dfrac{x+1}{3x-4}$.
$f(5) = \dfrac{5+1}{3(5)-4}$
Step 2: Simplify the expression $f(5) = \dfrac{5+1}{3(5)-4}$. 
$f(5) = \dfrac{6}{15-4}$
$f(5) = \dfrac{6}{15-4} = \dfrac{6}{11}$
Step 3: Simplify the expression $f(5) = \dfrac{6}{11}$. 
$f(5) = \dfrac{6}{11}$
Step 4: 
$f(5) = \dfrac{6}{11}$
$f(5) = \dfrac{6}{11}$
Step 5: $f(5) = \dfrac{6}{11}$
No additional step is needed as the solution is already simplified in Step 3.
Final Answer: $\boxed{\dfrac{6}{11}}$
